What Is Low-Code/No-Code? Build Apps Without Writing Code! In today’s digital age, where technology plays a pivotal role in every sector of the economy, the ability to rapidly develop applications and digital solutions has become a crucial factor in determining an organization’s competitiveness. Whether it’s SMEs, retail businesses, or even government agencies looking to improve public services, one of the most effective technologies meeting these demands is the low code platform and no code platform—both of which are gaining widespread popularity around the world. What Is Low Code? Low code refers to a low code platform that enables users to develop applications or business systems with minimal coding—sometimes none at all. Users can design workflows, databases, and user interfaces using intuitive drag-and-drop tools. The strength of low code lies in its balance between ease of use and customization capabilities. While it is beginner-friendly, it still allows those with coding experience to extend and tailor the application as needed. This makes it a great choice for organizations that require flexibility and already have some level of developer resources in-house. What Is a No Code Platform? A no code platform takes it a step further, enabling users to build applications without writing a single line of code. It’s designed to empower non-technical staff—such as marketing teams, operations staff, or internal department personnel—to create systems using pre-built templates and ready-to-use features. The major benefit of a no code platform is that it reduces the workload on IT departments and encourages the rise of citizen developers, allowing employees outside of IT to actively participate in digital transformation. Comparison Table: Low Code vs. No Code Platform Business and Organizational Benefits of Low Code and No Code Platforms Reduced development time and cost: Cut down on the need", "layout": {"sections": ["What Is Low Code and No Code? Key Differences Explai